[[Image:American Ambulance Association Logo.jpg|thumb|right|200px|AAA logo]] '''The [[United States|American]] [[Ambulance]] Association''' ('''AAA''') is a [[trade association]] for the [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] industry. The AAA is based in [[McLean, Virginia]] and was founded in 1979.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ambulance.org/our-mission/ |title=American Ambulance Association: Our Mission |last=American Ambulance Association |first= |date= |website=ambulance.org |publisher=American Ambulance Association |access-date=May 16, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>
The AAA's website states that its mission is "to promote health care policies that ensure excellence in the ambulance services industry and provide research, education and communications programs to enable its members to effectively address the needs of the communities they serve."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ambulance.org/our-mission/ |title=American Ambulance Association: Our Mission |last=American Ambulance Association |first= |date= |website=ambulance.org |publisher=American Ambulance Association |access-date=May 16, 2018 |quote=}}</ref> As part of this mission, the AAA manages the "Stars of Life" program, an annual awards program that recognizes "ambulance professionals who have gone above and beyond the call of duty in service to their communities or the EMS profession."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://stars.ambulance.org/ |title=Stars of Life 2018: American Ambulance Association |last=American Ambulance Association |first= |date= |website=ambulance.org |publisher=American Ambulance Association |access-date=May 16, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>
In 2015, the AAA issued its first recommendations for diversity and intercultural communication, noting that the primarily white, male, English-speaking EMS workforce underserved some population sectors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/24/nyregion/a-brooklyn-ambulance-service-speaks-chinese-like-its-patients.html |title=A Brooklyn Ambulance Service Speaks Chinese, Like Its Patients |last=Nir |first=Sarah Maslin |date=May 23, 2016 |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times |access-date=May 16, 2018 |quote=In New York and around the country, emergency responders have historically been white and male, said Scott Moore, a human resources and operations consultant with the American Ambulance Association, a national trade organization, and an emergency medical technician for 26 years. Beyond translating words, Mr. Moore said, a diverse emergency response fleet can add cultural competency to how their work is done … Last year, Mr. Moore’s organization issued its first handbook for intercultural communication. }}</ref>
The AAA holds an annual conference and awards dinner, where it gives annual awards such as the Patient and Employee Safety award to ambulance companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scottsdaleindependent.com/news/scottsdale-ambulance-technology-receives-national-ems-safety-award/|title=Scottsdale ambulance technology receives national EMS safety award|date=2018-08-28|work=Scottsdale Independent|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-US}}</ref> Another award is the Star of Life award. In March 2017, an ambulance was hit by a Jeep Cherokee in Mississippi, nearly killing a paramedic. Paramedic Jimmy Miller was awarded the AAA Star of Life award for outstanding service after surviving the wreck, which should have killed him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.clarionledger.com/story/news/local/2018/08/08/wreck-nearly-kills-paramedic-who-earns-national-award-valor/872018002/|title=AMR paramedic survives near-fatal wreck, receives national award for valor|work=The Clarion Ledger|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en}}</ref>
