[[Colonel]] [[The Honourable]] '''John Edmund Erskine''' (30 March 1662 &ndash; 13 January 1743), of [[Cardross, Argyll and Bute|Cardross]], was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] soldier and politician.
==Background== Born at Cardross, Scotland on 30 March 1662, a younger son of [[David Erskine, 2nd Lord Cardross]], by his secone wife, Mary Bruce, daughter of Sir George Bruce of Carnock.<ref>''Publications of the Scottish History Society, Volume 14'' p. xiii T. and A. Constable, 1893 [https://books.google.com/books?id=NAQdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PR13&dq=lord+cardross+mary+bruce&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwioz5vH_frKAhUH6mMKHeWzCKoQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&q=lord%20cardross%20mary%20bruce&f=false]</ref><ref>Erskine, John. ''Journal of the Hon. John Erskine of Carnock, 1683-1687'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=K0wNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR13&dq=lord+cardross+mary+bruce+carnock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3ybSm_vrKAhUOxWMKHdCuBCcQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=lord%20cardross%20mary%20bruce%20carnock&f=false]</ref><ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> His father was a member of a [[cadet#Etymology|cadet]] branch of the [[Earl of Buchan|Earls of Buchan]].
==Career== Erskine's strongly [[Church of Scotland|Presbyterian]] sympathies led him to choose the winning sides during the [[Glorious Revolution]] of 1688 and the deliberations prior to the [[Acts of Union 1707|Act of Union]] of 1707.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> He fled from [[Scotland]] to join the army of [[William III of England|William of Orange]], where he was given command of a [[Infantry|Regiment of Foot]].<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> He landed in [[England]] with William's invading army in 1698, the beginning of the Glorious Revolution. In return for his service, he was given further commands in William's army, made governor of [[Stirling Castle|Stirling]] and [[Dumbarton Castle|Dumbarton]] castles.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> In 1695, he was appointed a director of the [[Company of Scotland]], and, in the following year, was sent to [[Holland]] and other parts of the continent, to manage the affairs of the company.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}
Erskine was dubbed The Black Colonel.<ref>Erskine, Beatrice ''The Memoirs of Sir David Erskine of Cardross,'' pp. 73-79. London: T. Fisher Unwin, 1926 [https://books.google.com/books?id=CN0uAAAAIAAJ&q=%27Black%27+Sir+John+Erskine+of+Cardross&dq=]</ref>
His portrait can be found hanging at The National Trust for Scotland, Royal Burgh of Culross.[https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/black-sir-john-of-erskine-of-cardross-197338]
==Family== Erskine was married four times. He married as his first wife Jane, daughter of William Mure of Caldwell, in 1690.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> After Jane's early death the same year he married as his second wife Anna, daughter of Sir William Dundas of Kincavel.<ref>www.peerage.com [http://www.thepeerage.com/p5406.htm#i54056]</ref><ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> They had six sons and a daughter.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> One of his sons was the great jurist [[John Erskine of Carnock]], father to [[John Erskine (theologian)|John Erskine DD]], leader of the [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical Party]] in the 18th Century [[Church of Scotland|Scottish Church]]. After Anna's death in June 1723 he married thirdly Lilias, daughter of Sir George Stirling of Keir and widow of John Murray, in 1725.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> There were no children from this marriage.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> After Lilias's death in March 1729, he married as his fourth wife Mary, daughter of Charles Stewart of Duncarn, in November 1729.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> They had at least one son, Charles, who died unmarried. Erskine died at Edinburgh on 13 January 1743, aged 80.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref> His fourth wife died in September 1772.<ref>Foster, Joseph ''Members of Parliament, Scotland: Including the Minor Barons, the Commissioners for the Shires, and the Commissioners for the Burghs, 1357-1882,'' p. 128. London: Hazell, Watson and Viney, 1882 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vbsUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=%22john+erskine%22+anna+dundas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE2cai__rKAhUQw2MKHXoAAxYQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20erskine%22%20anna%20dundas&f=false]</ref>
