{{Infobox person | name = Norman Braman | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1932|08|23}} | birth_place = [[West Chester, Pennsylvania]], U.S. | residence = [[Miami, Florida]], U.S. | nationality = United States | alma_mater = [[Temple University]] | occupation = Car dealer | known_for = Owner of the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] from 1985–1994 | networth = [[United States dollar|US $]] 2.5 [[1,000,000,000 (number)|billion]] (March 2018)<ref name="Forbes profile">{{cite web|title=Forbes profile: Norman Braman|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/norman-braman/|website=Forbes|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> | spouse = Irma Miller | children = 2 daughters | website = }}
'''Norman Braman''' (born August 23, 1932) is an American [[billionaire]] car dealer, art collector, and former owner of the [[Philadelphia Eagles]]. {{TOC left}} {{clear}}
==Early life and education== Braman was born in 1932 in [[West Chester, Pennsylvania]],<ref>The American Presidency Project, [http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=44305 Nomination of Norman Braman To Be Commissioner of Immigration and Naturalization] September 28, 1981</ref> and grew up in the [[Cobbs Creek]] section of [[Philadelphia]], where his father owned a barbershop. Braman's parents were both [[Jews]] who emigrated from Europe. His [[Romania]]n-born mother was a seamstress and his [[Poland|Polish]] father a barber.<ref name=miami>{{cite news|author=Gus Garcia Roberts|title=Bet on Norman Braman|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/2008-12-18/news/bet-on-norman-braman|work=The Miami New Times|date=December 18, 2008|accessdate=April 12, 2009}}</ref> Braman was a water boy in his teenage years at the Eagles training camp, which was then in West Chester.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} During the season, he would sneak into [[Shibe Park]] to watch the team play.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oaW8Rr5gpVEC&pg=PA147&lpg=PA147&dq=norman+braman#v=onepage&q=norman%20braman&f=false|first=Gordan|last=Forbes|title=Tales from the Eagles Sideline|pages=147|publisher=Sports Publishing |date=September 15, 2006|ISBN= 9781596701533}}</ref><ref name=sports>{{cite news|author= John Steinbreder|title=The Owners|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1993/09/13/129257/the-owners-a-few-of-them-are-household-names-some-of-them-youve-never-heard--of-all-of-them-are-rich-how-rich-in-the-following-pages-we-rank-93-team-owners-by-net-worth-from-the-biggest-billionaires-to-the-merest-of-millionaires|work=Sports Illustrated|date=September 13, 1993|accessdate=June 21, 2008}}</ref> Braman attended West Philadelphia High School and graduated from [[Temple University]] in 1955 with a degree in business administration.<ref name=philly>{{cite news|author=Peter Mucha|title=‘Richest Americans’ list includes 4 from Philly|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/breaking/103638234.html|work=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=September 23, 2010|accessdate=October 18, 2010}}</ref>
==Career== Braman began his career as a market research analyst for [[Seagram|Seagram's Distributors]] in 1955. A few years later he took an executive position at Bargaintown U.S.A. which he eventually acquired and turned into Keystone Stores, a chain of self-service variety stores in the Philadelphia area. In the mid-1960s he spearheaded the merger between his Keystone Stores business and Philadelphia Laboratories to create Philadelphia Pharmaceuticals and Cosmetics. Braman was appointed president and CEO of the new company. Acquisitions under his tenure at the company included Vitamix Pharmaceuticals, F.A. Martin and Company, and U.S. Cocoa Corporation. Braman stepped down from his position at Philadelphia Pharmaceuticals and Cosmetics in 1969 to pursue other interests.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaldealer.com/interview-with-norman-braman-owner-of-braman-enterprises |title=Interview with Norman Braman – Owner of Braman Enterprises|publisher=Emerald Expositions|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>
[[File:Bugatti Veyron @ Braman Motors, Miami FL - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|175px|A Bugatti Veyron sits in the showroom at one of Braman’s Miami dealerships]] Braman got his start in the automobile business in 1972 when he acquired controlling interest of Sharpe-Taylor Cadillac in [[Tampa, Florida]]. During these early years, Braman was mentored by well known car dealer and fellow Philadelphia native [[Victor Potamkin]]. In 1975, Braman bought the former Nolan Brown Cadillac in [[Miami, Florida]]. The following year, Braman took on his first import brands with the purchase of [[BMW]] and [[Rolls-Royce Motors|Rolls-Royce]] dealership C.R. Berry Motors and moved both franchises next to his Miami [[Cadillac]] dealership.<ref name="auto"/> By 1980, Braman had Cadillac, BMW, Rolls-Royce, [[Fiat Automobiles|Fiat]], [[Lancia]], and [[Toyota]] dealerships along the 2000 block of [[Biscayne Boulevard]] in Miami.
While continuing to expand his dealership holdings in the [[South Florida]] area, Braman has also added dealerships in [[Colorado]]. Today, Braman serves as chairman of Braman Management, an umbrella company for his automotive businesses that include more than 20 dealerships in [[Florida]] and Colorado selling [[Acura]], [[Audi]], [[Bentley]], BMW, [[Bugatti]], Cadillac, [[Genesis Motors|Genesis]], [[Honda]], [[Hyundai]], [[Kia Motors|Kia]], [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[Mini (marque)|MINI]], [[Porsche]] and Rolls-Royce.<ref name="bizjournals">{{cite news|author=Kevin Gale|title=JM Family Enterprises, Southern Wine & Spirits lead the list|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/stories/2004/08/02/focus1.html|work=South Florida Business Journal|date=August 2, 2004|accessdate=March 10, 2008}}</ref>
In addition to his retail automotive businesses, Braman had majority ownership of Austin Rover Cars of North America (ARCONA), the distributorship for [[Sterling (marque)|Sterling]] automobiles imported to the United States starting in 1987. The company's name was changed to Sterling Motor Cars in 1989 and closed in 1991 after sales of the [[Rover 800 Series|Rover 800]]-based Sterling 825/827 models failed to meet expectations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2014/03/17/lost-cars-of-the-1980s-sterling-825-and-827/|title=Lost Cars of the 1980s – Sterling 825 and 827|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=March 17, 2014|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>
==Philadelphia Eagles== Braman and his brother-in-law, Ed Leibowitz, became owners of the Philadelphia Eagles in April 1985 having acquired them from [[Leonard Tose]] for a reported $65 million. Initially, Braman owned 65% of the team while Leibowitz owned 35%. In July 1986, Braman bought out Leibowitz’s interest. During Braman's ownership, the Eagles made playoff appearances in 1988, 1989, 1990 and 1992. They were [[NFC East]] division champions in 1988.
In 1994, Braman agreed to sell the team to a group lead by movie producer [[Jeffrey Lurie]]. The reported selling price was $185 million, a record for a sports team franchise at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/07/sports/pro-football-eagles-purchased-for-record-amount.html|title=Eagles Sold for Record, Reported at $185 million|publisher=The New York Times|date=April 7, 1994|accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref>
==Politics== He financially supported a [[recall election]] against Miami-Dade Mayor [[Carlos Alvarez (mayor)|Carlos Alvarez]] because of a huge property tax increase and pay hikes to Alvarez's top staffers.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} On March 15, 2011 close to 90% of those that turned out to vote that day in Miami-Dade County, voted to recall the mayor. It is believed to be one of the most lopsided recall elections in the history of American elections.<ref name=15MayrecallMH>{{cite news|last=Haggman|first=Matthew|title=9 of 10 say ‘yes’ to ousting Alvare|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/03/15/2117129/9-of-10-say-yes-to-ousting-alvarez.html|accessdate=16 May 2011|newspaper=[[Miami Herald]]|date=15 May 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316212716/http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/03/15/2117129/9-of-10-say-yes-to-ousting-alvarez.html|archivedate=16 March 2011|df=}}</ref>
In 2012, Braman established political groups to campaign against four incumbent [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]] commissioners with $440,000 in funding, focusing on the commissioners' support for the controversial [[Marlins Park]] project and a property tax hike in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article1941269.html|title=Norman Braman’s money gives challengers better shot at Miami-Dade Commission seats|last=Rabin|first=Charles|date=2012-07-16|work=Miami Herald|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en}}</ref>
Braman was a supporter of [[Marco Rubio]],<ref name="NYT5915">{{cite news|author1=Michael Barbaro and Steve Eder|title=Billionaire Lifts Marco Rubio, Politically and Personally|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/10/us/billionaire-lifts-marco-rubio-politically-and-personally.html|accessdate=May 10, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=May 9, 2015}}</ref> and was considering spending anywhere between {{USD}}10 million to {{USD}}25 million in support of [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign, 2016|his 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marco Rubio's secret weapon|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/04/marco-rubio-2016-campaign-norman-braman-117134.html?hp=t1_r|publisher=Politico|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> According to the acknowledgements in his autobiography, Rubio has thanked Braman for being a supporter, and Braman has employed at one time or another Marco Rubio's wife,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/meet-marco-rubios-wife-jeanette-dousdebes-shares-surprising/story?id=30306521|title=6 Surprises Marco Rubio's Wife Shared About Her Husband|first=A. B. C.|last=News|date=7 August 2015|website=ABC News|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> [[Jeanette Dousdebes Rubio]], at the Braman family's charitable foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reading Of Marco Rubio's Biography|url=http://kenfields.net/reading-of-marco-rubios-biography/|publisher=kenfields.net.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211152906/http://kenfields.net/reading-of-marco-rubios-biography/|archivedate=2015-12-11|df=}}</ref>
==Philanthropy== Braman and his wife, Irma, established the Norman and Irma Braman Family Foundation, which primarily helps fund medical and educational projects throughout the world.{{fact|date=June 2018}} It is headed by their daughter Debra Wechsler.{{fact|date=June 2018}}
Braman, an art collector, also serves as president of the Irma and Norman Braman Art Foundation, which supports the arts and culture in and around the Miami area.{{fact|date=June 2018}}
==Personal life== Braman is married to Irma Miller.<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ldnews/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=137001770#fbLoggedOut Lebanon Daily News: "Sophie Miller Obituary"] on December 6, 2009</ref> They have two daughters:<ref>[http://www.myfloridahouse.com/Sections/Documents/loaddoc.aspx?FileName=_h9123__.docx&DocumentType=Bill&BillNumber=9123&Session=2008 The Florida House of Representatives House Resolution 9123] – A resolution honoring Norman Braman for his philanthropy on behalf of the people of the State of Florida | 2008</ref> Debra Wechsler and Suzi Lustgarten.<ref>[http://giving.chop.edu/site/PageNavigator/Gift_of_Childhood/Our_Stories/Donor_Stories/donor_braman_center_of_excellence.html The Children's Hospital of Philadelphia Foundation: A New Center of Excellence – The Suzi and Scott Lustgarten Center for GI Motility] retrieved March 24, 2013</ref>
